And started rebuilding the house.

# EIW Correspondence Archive — 2021  
## The Year It Broke (and Rebuilt)

---

## Year Overview

If 2020 was hope stretched thin,

2021 was the year the tension snapped.

This is the year:

- Wave 2 launches.
- Tor finally answers.
- Publisher doors close.
- Brendan leaves.
- The agent relationship dissolves.
- You pay for real editorial truth.
- The Keeper stops being sacred and becomes material.

2021 is fracture.

But also foundation.

---

# Phase I — January: Momentum Returns

You begin the year in Costa Rica.

Surfing.
Writing.
Revising.

You send the second “just in case” backup to Adam.

Subject line:

> “Safe Keeping.”

Wave 2 launches in February.

New editors.
New hope.

Brendan writes:

> “Into two editors already… MOMO.”

You reply:

> “MOMENTUM!!!”

You believe again.

---

# Phase II — The Tor Door Closes

April 20, 2021.

Ali Fisher at Tor finally responds.

Fourteen months after submission.

She apologizes.
She read it.
She passes.

You write:

> “Damn. Tor was a childhood dream of mine.”

Brendan clarifies:

> “Once an editor passes, it's a pass for the house.”

Tor is closed.

Not forever.

But for this book.

That one lands.

---

# Phase III — The Genre Problem Becomes Structural

Rejections sharpen.

Tricia Nirwani:
> “More suited to a full-on YA publisher.”

Sourcebooks:
> “Voice feels young for YA.”

Adult editors hesitate.
YA editors hesitate.

You begin naming the truth:

The book doesn’t fit cleanly.

It’s too dark for traditional YA.
Too young for adult.
Too minimalist for epic fantasy.
Too epic for minimalism.

The story is yours.

The category is unclear.

And publishing is a category machine.

---

# Phase IV — The Agent Leaves

June 22, 2021.

Brendan writes:

> “I am leaving Assemble at the end of the month.”

He will send the submission list.

You reply:

> “Still processing.”

This is not betrayal.
Not drama.
Not scandal.

It is structural.

The person steering the ship is stepping off.

Six editors still hold the manuscript.

You have no agent.

And no deal.

The quiet reality arrives.

---

# Phase V — The Honest Email

August 9, 2021.

You write to Rebecca Brewer:

> “I've been navigating this publishing black box alone for so long now. I did not feel creatively or strategically supported by my agent.”

That sentence matters.

It is not blame.

It is clarity.

You realize something important:

Representation is not the same as alignment.

---

# Phase VI — Paying for Truth

You hire Rebecca Brewer.

$2,500.

October 1 deadline.

You deliberately avoid speaking first.

You write:

> “I am rather charismatic and I fear my passion and personality are why those around me love the book so much.”

You want the manuscript judged.

Not the performance.

That is growth.

---

# Phase VII — The Editorial Letter

October 1, 2021.

The letter arrives.

It is not brutal.

It is not dismissive.

It is accurate.

Key notes:

- The beginning is too thin.
- Stakes are unclear.
- The heart of Kris’s journey is not fully shaped.
- Worldbuilding lacks grounding.
- POV transitions are confusing.
- Length should be ~100k words.

She writes:

> “One of the best written books I've gotten to work on recently.”

But:

The structure is not yet whole.

You forward the letter to family.

> “Not to be shared. Still processing.”

You pay the remaining $1,250 the next morning.

You do not argue.

You do not defend.

You go quiet.

---

# Phase VIII — Experimental Mode

Six weeks later:

> “I'm in a very experimental mode that I want to stay in for now.”

You delay the debrief call.

You start worldbuilding.

Not revising scenes.

Rebuilding foundation.

You begin loving the Codex more than the manuscript.

That shift is seismic.

---

# Phase IX — The Codex Backup

December 29, 2021.

You send Adam not the manuscript.

The Codex.

The world.

The lore.

The structure.

Adam replies:

> “Consider her Kept safely!!!!”

But it isn’t The Keeper anymore.

It’s becoming something else.

